# Environment:

OS: Debian 9.
SDK: 2018-04-13 

# Description of the issue:

The issue occurs when calling the IoTHubRegistryManager_GetDevice function with a device ID that does not exist in the IoT Hub.

I would expect it to return the value IOTHUB_REGISTRYMANAGER_DEVICE_NOT_EXIST, but what it actually returns is IOTHUB_REGISTRYMANAGER_HTTP_STATUS_ERROR .

What I want is a "create if not exists" scenario, I was hoping to use the GetDevice function to identify when a device does not already exist and then use CreateDevice to create the device.  It looks like the SDK should support this, so I was surprised by the result returned by GetDevice when the device doesn't exist -- is this intentional or a bug?  Is there a better way to do a "create if not exists" using the SDK?

Calling the GetDevice function with a device ID for a device that does not exist also results in Errors being logged, which is not desirable for this use case.

# Code sample exhibiting the issue:

IOTHUB_SERVICE_CLIENT_AUTH_HANDLE serviceHandle = IoTHubServiceClientAuth_CreateFromConnectionString ("...");
IOTHUB_REGISTRYMANAGER_HANDLE registryHandle = IoTHubRegistryManager_Create (serviceHandle);
IOTHUB_DEVICE device;
IOTHUB_REGISTRYMANAGER_RESULT result;
result = IoTHubRegistryManager_GetDevice (registryHandle, "new-device", &device);

