I'm using the https://www.olimex.com/Products/IoT/ESP8266-EVB-BAT-BOX/open-source-hardware esp8266 with the current development homie firmware and the sketch that is shown at the end.
The sketch runs fine for a couple of hours or days respectively, and then suddenly starts to resetting itself every 15 seconds or so. I did observe that on two different devices. I couldn't get serial output until now that would give more information on the cause of reset (hope to get to that when it happens again). From what I found so far on the internet, it all points to a watchdog timer issue. Did anybody have a similar experience?

I had a similar sketch running with the stable 1.5 homie release and I didn't see experience any device resets. For the 2.0 sketch, I changed to bring down the relay in the loopHandler because the following sequence didn't work in relayToggleHandler any more:

```
  if (value == "1" && digitalRead(PIN_RELAY) == LOW) {
    digitalWrite(PIN_RELAY, HIGH);
    delay(250);
    digitalWrite(PIN_RELAY, LOW);
 }
```
The relay didn't go to HIGH and back to LOW (it stayed LOW), I suppose that is related to the asynchronious nature in homie 2.0?


**Homie 2.0.0 sketch:**
```
/*
 * Olimex esp8266 development board ESP8266 EVB-BAT 
 * Firmware for Homie 2.0.0 with basic push button functionality.
 * 
 */

#include <Homie.h>

const int PIN_RELAY = 5;
const int PIN_BUTTON = 0;
unsigned long relayLastOn = 0;

HomieNode relayNode("relay", "relay");

bool relayToggleHandler(HomieRange range, String value) {
  if (value == "1" && digitalRead(PIN_RELAY) == LOW) {
    digitalWrite(PIN_RELAY, HIGH);
    relayNode.setProperty("on").send("true");
    relayNode.setProperty("toggle").send("1");
    relayLastOn = millis();
    Serial << "Relay was toggled." << endl;
  } else {
    return false;
  }
  return true;
}

void loopHandler() {
  // bring the relay down to LOW after 250 ms, delay should not be called in any loop function
  if ( digitalRead(PIN_RELAY) == HIGH ) {
    unsigned long currentMillis = millis();
    if ( (unsigned long)(currentMillis - relayLastOn) >= 250) {
      digitalWrite(PIN_RELAY, LOW);
      relayNode.setProperty("on").send("false");
      relayLastOn = currentMillis;
    }
  }
}

void setup() {
  Serial.begin(115200);
  Serial << endl << endl;

  // setup relay and button PIN
  pinMode(PIN_BUTTON, INPUT);
  pinMode(PIN_RELAY, OUTPUT);
  digitalWrite(PIN_RELAY, LOW);

  // Homie settings
  Homie_setFirmware("olimex-esp8266", "1.0.0");
  //Homie.disableLedFeedback();

  // reset device when pressing pin button for 5 sec (default)
  Homie.setResetTrigger(PIN_BUTTON, LOW, 5000);

  // relay only exposes a toggle property that
  // Use devices/dev-id/relay/toggle -> 1 to observe the relay
  // Use devices/dev-id/relay/toggle/set <- 1 to trigger the relay
  relayNode.advertise("toggle").settable(relayToggleHandler);
  relayNode.advertise("on");

  Homie.setLoopFunction(loopHandler);
  Homie.setup();
}

void loop() {
  Homie.loop();
}
```

The `start` event is not sent to all devices, only the last one that's defined.

```
"use strict";

var Cylon = require("cylon");

var bum = Cylon.robot({
    name: "Bum",
    connections: [
        { name: "digispark", adaptor: "digispark" }
    ],
    devices: [
        { name: "blinky", driver: "led",    pin: 1 },
        { name: "door1",  driver: "button", pin: 4 },
        { name: "door2",  driver: "button", pin: 5 },
    ],
    work: function(my) {
        my.door1.on("start",  function() { console.log("door1 started");  } );
        my.door2.on("start",  function() { console.log("door2 started");  } );
        my.blinky.on("start", function() { console.log("blinky started"); } );

        every(100, function() {
            my.blinky.toggle();
        });
    }
});

bum.on("working", function() { console.log("bum working"); });

Cylon.start();
```

In the console output I should see the `<device name> started` message for each device, but instead I only see it for `door2`.  If I re-order the `devices` array, the last one is the one that gets the `started event`.

Hi,
this code don't work anymore with development branch and sleep time 0 to sleep forever:
```
// Sleep until someone pushes the sensor buttons
boolean smart = true;
sleep(digitalPinToInterrupt(BUTTON_INT_PIN), FALLING, 0, smart);
```
MyDebug response to sleep call is: `!MCO:SLP:NTL` (// sleeping not possible, no time left) and sleep is skipped.

Problem is in file MySensors\core\MySensorsCore.cpp, line 588:
```
	if (smartSleep) {
		// sleeping time left?
		if (sleepingTimeMS < ((uint32_t)MY_SMART_SLEEP_WAIT_DURATION_MS)) {
			wait(sleepingMS);
			CORE_DEBUG(PSTR("!MCO:SLP:NTL\n"));	// sleeping not possible, no time left
			return MY_SLEEP_NOT_POSSIBLE;
		}
```
Solution:
Line 588 should also check for 0 which means sleep forever.
`		if (sleepingTimeMS > 0 && sleepingTimeMS < ((uint32_t)MY_SMART_SLEEP_WAIT_DURATION_MS)) {
`

