## Bug Report
Calls to BLE.setScanTimeout or BLE.setScanParameters fail for all values of timeout stating the interval is out of range.

### Expected Behavior
Firmware writers should be able to adjust ble scan parameters such as window, interval, or timeout.
### Observed Behavior
Calls fail with -1, log displays: `000022690 [hal.ble] ERROR: params->interval < 0x0004`

### Steps to Reproduce
Call BLE.setScanTimeout or BLE.setScanParameters. The bounds checking in `BleObject::Observer::setScanParams` looks reversed and always causes the interval check to fail.

firmware: 1.3.0-rc

### Test App

```c
SerialLogHandler handler (LOG_LEVEL_ALL);

void setup() {
  // A minimal test case to reproduce the issue is super helpful!
BleScanParams scanParams;
scanParams.version = BLE_API_VERSION;
scanParams.size = sizeof(BleScanParams);;
BLE.getScanParameters (&scanParams);
scanParams.interval = 10;
scanParams.timeout = 10;
auto result = BLE.setScanParameters (&scanParams);
Serial.printf("setScanParameters result: %u\n", result);

result = BLE.setScanTimeout (100);
Serial.printf("setScanTimeout result: %u\n", result);
}

void loop() {
auto startTime = millis ();
auto results = BLE.scan ();
auto stopTime = millis ();
Serial.printf ("Spent %u millis scanning BLE devices\n", stopTime - startTime);
}
```

### Output
```
0000021739 [hal.ble] ERROR: params->interval < 0x0004 failed: -270
setScanParameters result: 4294967026
0000021743 [hal.ble] ERROR: params->interval < 0x0004 failed: -270
setScanTimeout result: 4294967026
Spent 5001 millis scanning BLE devices
```

It seems like there is an issue with control of the RGB led, that depends on what order `brightness` and `color` are called in.  If brightness is called first, it works as expected, however if you call color and then brightness, the brightness is not adjusted.  For example:

```
void setup() {
    Serial.begin(9600);
    while (!Serial.available());
    RGB.control(true);
    RGB.color(0, 0, 0);
    RGB.brightness(0);
}

void loop() {
    RGB.color(255,255,255);
    Serial.println(0);
    RGB.brightness(0);
    delay(1000);
    RGB.brightness(63);
    Serial.println(63);
    delay(1000);
    RGB.brightness(127);
    Serial.println(127);
    delay(1000);
    RGB.brightness(191);
    Serial.println(191);
    delay(1000);
    Serial.println(255);
    RGB.brightness(255);
    delay(1000);
}
```

This code won't turn on the LED until the second loop, and then will stay at full brightness.  It only seems to be recognizing `RGB.brightness(255)` from the end of the loop, and `RGB.color(255,255,255)` from the beginning. See https://community.spark.io/t/rgb-brightness-doesnt-seem-to-be-working-solved/6303

Please see the following thread:

https://community.spark.io/t/time-zone-not-working/6572

The code is:

``` cpp
void setup() {
    Serial.begin(9600);
}

void loop() {
    Time.zone(-1);
    unsigned char const DEC_BASE = static_cast<unsigned char>(DEC);
    Serial.println( "tn: " + String(Time.hour(),DEC_BASE) );
    Time.zone(5);
    Serial.println( "tn: " + String(Time.hour(),DEC_BASE) );
    Serial.println("");
    delay(2000);
};
```

A work-around is to call Spark.timeSync(); but doing that too often seems to knock the cloud offline briefly.

### Problem

Socket operations, such as `socket_close()`, may cause a hard fault when performed after a WiFi reset.

### Solution

Invalidate all sockets when WiFi is being turned off. It is important to keep socket handles allocated via `socket_create()` valid.

### Steps to Test

The following application should not cause a hard fault or deadlock:
```cpp
#include "application.h"

SYSTEM_MODE(SEMI_AUTOMATIC)

namespace {

const Serial1LogHandler logHandler(115200, LOG_LEVEL_WARN, {
    { "app", LOG_LEVEL_ALL }
});

system_tick_t lastMillis = 0;
bool done = false;

} // namespace

void setup() {
    Log.info("setup()");
}

void loop() {
    if (done) {
        if (millis() - lastMillis >= 3000) {
            Log.info("loop()");
            lastMillis = millis();
        }
        return;
    }
    done = true;

    Log.info("WiFi.connect()");
    WiFi.connect();

    Log.info("socket_create()");
    const sock_handle_t sock = socket_create(AF_INET, SOCK_STREAM, IPPROTO_TCP, 53, NIF_DEFAULT);
    if (!socket_handle_valid(sock)) {
        Log.error("socket_create() failed");
        return;
    }

    Log.info("socket_connect()");
    sockaddr_t addr = {};
    addr.sa_family = AF_INET;
    addr.sa_data[0] = 0;
    addr.sa_data[1] = 53;
    addr.sa_data[2] = 8;
    addr.sa_data[3] = 8;
    addr.sa_data[4] = 8;
    addr.sa_data[5] = 8;
    const auto r = socket_connect(sock, &addr, sizeof(addr));
    if (r != 0) {
        Log.error("socket_connect() failed");
        return;
    }

    Log.info("WiFi.off()");
    WiFi.off();

    Log.info("WiFi.connect()");
    WiFi.connect();

    Log.info("socket_close()");
    const auto r2 = socket_close(sock);
    if (r2 != 0) {
        Log.error("socket_close() failed");
        return;
    }
}
```

